  "details": {
    "heading": "Power Settings",
    "description": [
      {
        "text": "Adversaries may impair a system's ability to hibernate, reboot, or shut down in order to extend access to infected machines. When a computer enters a dormant state, some or all software and hardware may cease to operate which can disrupt malicious activity.",
        "reference": {
          "number": 1,
          "url": "https://www.avg.com/en/signal/should-you-shut-down-sleep-or-hibernate-your-pc-or-mac-laptop",
          "title": "AVG. (n.d.). Should You Shut Down, Sleep or Hibernate Your PC or Mac Laptop?. Retrieved June 8, 2023."
        }
      },
      {
        "text": "Adversaries may abuse system utilities and configuration settings to maintain access by preventing machines from entering a state, such as standby, that can terminate malicious activity.",
        "references": [
          {
            "number": 2,
            "url": "https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-hardware/design/device-experiences/powercfg-command-line-options?adlt=strict",
            "title": "Microsoft. (2021, December 15). Powercfg command-line options. Retrieved June 5, 2023."
          },
          {
            "number": 3,
            "url": "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/systemd-sleep.conf.5.html",
            "title": "Man7. (n.d.). systemd-sleep.conf(5) — Linux manual page. Retrieved June 7, 2023."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "For example, powercfg controls all configurable power system settings on a Windows system and can be abused to prevent an infected host from locking or shutting down.",
        "references": [
          {
            "number": 4,
            "url": "https://securityintelligence.com/news/two-new-monero-malware-attacks-target-windows-and-android-users/",
            "title": "Douglas Bonderud. (2018, September 17). Two New Monero Malware Attacks Target Windows and Android Users. Retrieved June 5, 2023."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Adversaries may also extend system lock screen timeout settings.",
        "references": [
          {
            "number": 5,
            "url": "https://blogs.vmware.com/security/2022/11/batloader-the-evasive-downloader-malware.html",
            "title": "Bethany Hardin, Lavine Oluoch, Tatiana Vollbrecht. (2022, November 14). BATLOADER: The Evasive Downloader Malware. Retrieved June 5, 2023."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Other relevant settings, such as disk and hibernate timeout, can be similarly abused to keep the infected machine running even if no user is active.",
        "references": [
          {
            "number": 6,
            "url": "https://www.avira.com/en/blog/coinloader-a-sophisticated-malware-loader-campaign",
            "title": "Avira. (2019, November 28). CoinLoader: A Sophisticated Malware Loader Campaign. Retrieved June 5, 2023."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Aware that some malware cannot survive system reboots, adversaries may entirely delete files used to invoke system shut down or reboot.",
        "references": [
          {
            "number": 7,
            "url": "https://www.fortinet.com/blog/threat-research/condi-ddos-botnet-spreads-via-tp-links-cve-2023-1389",
            "title": "Joie Salvio and Roy Tay. (2023, June 20). Condi DDoS Botnet Spreads via TP-Link's CVE-2023-1389. Retrieved September 5, 2023."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
